Locality: Wheeler Pass via East Basin to route 071
Observation Details: 75 plus Chukar popped onto the road from the left East side and started moving to the North in front of the vehicle. They would get backed up as they waited for those in the front to descend into the desert grass beneath the Joshua trees. Once they were within the grass it was difficult to see them. A few flew and I was able to see where they were. All were immature. The black bars on the flanks were not fully developed. The same with the black border on the throat  and the legs and bill were not fully developed. Instead of a red bill, their bills were pinkish red with some black in the bills. The legs were not red but pinkiish. They travel at a very fast pace in a group. I was a distance away when I took some photos of them crossing the road. I could hear their "kakakaka" sounds. No loud harsh calls and no PITCH-oo-whidoo that you usually can hear from a distance away.It was a constant flow of birds popping up from the left side of the road and moving across the road

Observation Details: We heard Chukar calls from the hillside opposite the highway from our location along the river and began scanning the rocky and grassy slopes for the bird(s). Sherrie finally found one standing in the shade of the only tree in the area. We thought there might be more than one, and when I photographed them it turned out to be a pair with at least three partially-feathered chicks. Later, I found another immature bird on the rocks near the tree. It was fully feathered and appeared to be as large as the adult birds seen earlier, but lacked most of the black markings on the neck and had reduced black and  contrast to the markings on the sides. The photos are poor, but perhaps not so bad considering the birds were over 140 m away as measured later using Google Earth.

Media notes: Don Manson photo
Observation Details: This bird spent the entire winter in a residential neighborhood in Revelstoke, sheltering under backyard decks, foraging under bird feeders, and putting the run on domestic cats. It departed in spring not to be seen again. A partridge-like bird with a sharp black line running through a red eye and matching bill colour. The legs were also vivid red with long red talons and it ran from protected site to protected site with a leg extended forward gait that covered ground quickly. It left obvious long-toed tracks tracks in the snow. It preferred to run than fly.

Media notes: Very poor quality cell phone image. Bird was observed for 5 minutes at very close range, sometimes within 3 m. Very active, running behind snowbank, onto road, and back again. Finally flushed and flew along highway into forest. Distinctive rusty edges on tail end in flight final confirmation.
Observation Details: Bird was on Highway 5 exactly 10.0 km north of the Blue River Airport helicopter hangar. We turned around and went back to confirm. Definitely a chukar, red bill and legs, distinctive black stripe through eye on neck, stripes on sides. It ran along highway and snowbanks. Grainy photo attached. A VERY long way from where it should be. Totally wrong type of habitat. Lived 3 years in Kamloops where I saw this species regularly.
